Rapper extraordinaire Kwesta will have to consider a security upgrade at his Midrand home, in Jozi.This after thugs allegedly broke into his home and stole belongings worth R22 000.The Spirit hitmaker opened a case of burglary at the Midrand Police Station, claiming that thugs had helped themselves to his valuables. including his 55 inch sliver smart television set, three speakers and a Play Station console, just before his summer gigs.if(typeof za24_DisplayAd != "undefined") za24_DisplayAd("300x250","2");<a href="https://pubads.g.doubleclick.net/gampad/jump?iu=0&sz=1&c=234" target="_blank"><img src="https://pubads.g.doubleclick.net/gampad/ad?iu=0&sz=1&c=234" border="0" alt=""></a>The popular lyricist, whose real name is Senzo Vilakazi, told police he left the house with everything in order, and got the shock of his life when he was alerted by estate security guards that thieves had raided his home.“I left, leaving my wife and daughter in the house. And everything was in order. Around 4.30am the next morning, I returned home and went straight to bed without noticing anything.“Around 5.30am, the same morning, I was woken up by the estate security officers to alert me that the sliding doors were half-open."On the same date I was woken up by my helper notifying me that some items were missing in the TV room,” his statement reads.Police spokesperson, Matome Tlamela, said: “There have not been any arrests because we couldn’t get a positive lead to arrest any suspects. But investigations continue,” she said.Kwesta’s manager Pheko Kgengoe refused to comment.Kwesta couldn’t be reached for comment at the time of going to print.